    {
        "content": "<p>The concepts of a 2-adjunction with Hom-equivalences or Hom-adjunctions are called <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/biadjunction\">[[biadjunction]]</a> and <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/lax%202-adjunction\">[[lax 2-adjunction]]</a> on the nlab,  there's also a bit of discussion and some sources.</p>",
        "id": 300085671,
        "sender_full_name": "Tobias Schmude",
        "timestamp": 1663828650
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think the main references would be:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>'A Coherent Approach to Pseudomonads' by Stephen Lack. In this paper, pseudoadjoints are defined and it is shown that every pseudoadjunction gives rise to a pseudomonad</li>\n<li>'Enriched categories, internal categories and change of base' by Dominic Verity also contains a section about adjunctions of bicategories (called 'Local adjunctions')</li>\n<li>'Biequivalences in tricategories' by Nick Gurski (and also his PhD thesis). This approach defines the notion of biequivalence in arbitrary tricategories. This is more general, but it also gives more complicated diagrams.</li>\n<li>'Pseudo Limits, Biadjoints, and Pseudo Algebras: Categorical Foundations of Conformal Field Theory' by Thomas Fiore also has some stuff about biadjoints, and here universal arrows are introduced and shown to give rise to left biadjoints.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 300094494,
        "sender_full_name": "Niels van der Weide",
        "timestamp": 1663833054
    },
